  <script src='bundled-git.js'></script>
</head>

<body>
  <div class=page-layout-header>
    <%- include('../partials/_header.ejs') %>
    <%- include('../partials/_nav.ejs') %>
  </div>


  <main class='page-layout-main'>
    <h2 class='page-heading'>Git</h2>

    <section class='git-commands-section'>
      <h3 class='section-heading'>Git Commands</h3>
      <p class='section-desc'>
        This is a record of the git commands I've used with examples of how I've used them.
        The plan is to at least dump placeholders on this page which I can return to and
        read up on / flesh out later on. I wanted to start doing this as git seems such a broad
        topic but you can do some cool stuff without having to know each and every command inside out.
      </p>

      <div class='git-command-container'>
        <h4 class='git-command-container__heading'>status</h4>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>
          Shows current branch, untracked files in red, tracked files in green.
          Also shows whether the local and remote branches are in sync.
        </p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git status</code>
      </div>

      <div class='git-command-container'>
        <h4 class='git-command-container__heading'>checkout</h4>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>Switches between branches / commits.</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git checkout branchName</code>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>To create then checkou a branch.</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git checkout -b newBranchName</code>
      </div>

      <div class='git-command-container'>
        <h4 class='git-command-container__heading'>diff</h4>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>To see the differences between two branches / commits.</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git diff branchOne branchTwo</code>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>Just see which files are different.</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git diff --name-only branchOne branchTwo</code>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>View difference between a local branch and remote</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git diff branchOne origin/branchTwo</code>
      </div>

      <div class='git-command-container'>
        <h4 class='git-command-container__heading'>log</h4>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>To view commit history. 'q' to exit from the log back into bash.</p>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>Use this to get commit names if you need to checkout or revert to them.</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git log</code>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>Short pretty format</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git log --pretty=short</code>
      </div>

      <div class='git-command-container'>
        <h4 class='git-command-container__heading'>remote</h4>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>To see the remote url</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git remote -v</code>
      </div>

      <div class='git-command-container'>
        <h4 class='git-command-container__heading'>add</h4>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>To add all modified files to staging area</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git add .</code>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>To add an individual file to staging area</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git add /examplePath/exampleFile.js</code>
      </div>

      <div class='git-command-container'>
        <h4 class='git-command-container__heading'>commit</h4>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>Creates a commit on current branch.</p>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>If the -m flag is not used default text editor will open.</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git commit -m "this is a commit message"</code>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>Edit to message of the most recent commit.</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git commit --ammend -m "edited commit message"</code>
      </div>

      <div class='git-command-container'>
        <h4 class='git-command-container__heading'>branch</h4>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>To view all branches and current branch.</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git branch</code>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>To create a new branch from the current branch.</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git branch newBranchName</code>
      </div>

      <div class='git-command-container'>
        <h4 class='git-command-container__heading'>set-upstream</h4>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>To set the remote for current branch.</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git branch --set-upstream-to=origin/branchName</code>
      </div>

      <div class='git-command-container'>
        <h4 class='git-command-container__heading'>push</h4>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>To push current branch up to the set remote.</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git push</code>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>To set the remote and push to it.</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git push -u origin branchName</code>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>
          To force push to the set remote. I've done this when the remote is has changes that
          would be lost but I don't care and want to overwrite the remote from local. Maybe After changing
          the directory structure. Git warns you that you could lose code. Use like below it can push to multiple
          branches I think and is dangerous as can lose commits. Probably avoid force pushing at all unless it's just yourself
          working on a repo. Better to normal push and solve conflicts.
        </p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git push -f</code>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>Force pushes to specified branch only.</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git push origin +branchName</code>
      </div>

      <div class='git-command-container'>
        <h4 class='git-command-container__heading'>fetch</h4>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>#placeholder</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git fetch</code>
      </div>

      <div class='git-command-container'>
        <h4 class='git-command-container__heading'>merge</h4>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>#placeholder</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git merge</code>
      </div>

      <div class='git-command-container'>
        <h4 class='git-command-container__heading'>pull</h4>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>#placeholder</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git pull</code>
      </div>

      <div class='git-command-container'>
        <h4 class='git-command-container__heading'>clone</h4>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>#placeholder</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git clone</code>
      </div>

      <div class='git-command-container'>
        <h4 class='git-command-container__heading'>reset</h4>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>#placeholder</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git reset</code>
      </div>

      <div class='git-command-container'>
        <h4 class='git-command-container__heading'>rebase</h4>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>#placeholder</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git rebase</code>
      </div>

      <div class='git-command-container'>
        <h4 class='git-command-container__heading'>revert</h4>
        <p class='git-command-container__desc'>#placeholder</p>
        <code class='git-command-container__example-code'>$ git revert</code>
      </div>

    </section>

  </main>


